'''Playing God''' refers to someone supposedly taking on the role of [[God]] for other purposes, also referred to as [[apotheosis]]. Alleged acts of playing God may include, for example, deciding who is to live or die in a situation where not everyone can be saved. Usually the expression is used to invoke a [[precautionary principle]] or to suggest that someone should refrain from a [[controversy|controversial]] action.{{citation needed|date=May 2013}}

[[Philip Ball]] wrote an article saying that "playing God" is a meaningless and dangerous cliché,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/2010/05/playing-god-is-a-meaningless-dangerous-cliche/ |title= "Playing God" is a meaningless, dangerous cliché |work=Prospect Magazine |publisher= |author=Philip Ball |date= May 24, 2010}}</ref> in the sense that it has no basis in [[theology]]. Instead it was adopted by [[theocon]]s from the 1931 film version of ''[[Frankenstein (1931 film)|Frankenstein]]'', and has been used by journalists to refer to things with which they do not agree. The idea is further discussed in Practical Ethics, a blog linked to Oxford University.<ref>{{cite web |title= Practical Ethics - Blog |date= May 26, 2010 |url= http://blog.practicalethics.ox.ac.uk/2010/05/is-playing-god-just-a-meaningless-phrase |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120203191701/http://blog.practicalethics.ox.ac.uk/2010/05/is-playing-god-just-a-meaningless-phrase |dead-url= yes |archivedate= February 3, 2012 }}</ref>

